{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533511"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:36:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:36:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14786"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14786"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.56,0.26,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109963"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7477"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14786"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92321"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1692"},{"type":"tags","id":"4252"},{"type":"tags","id":"4280"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44422"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109963"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with pain and swelling over his right hand. He was involved in a physical altercation eight hours ago and sustained an injury to his hand when he punched someone in the mouth. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. There is a 1 cm laceration over the third metacarpophalangeal joint with surrounding erythema and tenderness. There is no purulent discharge, lymphangitis, or reduced range of movement in the fingers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate empirical antibiotic therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cephalexin","Amoxicillin-clavulanate","Flucloxacillin","Metronidazole","Benzylpenicillin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clenched-fist injury, which should be considered a human bite injury due to contact with oral flora. These injuries require empirical antibiotic therapy that covers both oral and skin organisms, even in the absence of obvious infection, due to the high risk of complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate empirical antibiotic as it provides coverage against both oral flora (including \u003Cem\u003EEikenella corrodens\u003C/em\u003E) and skin organisms (including \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species). The addition of clavulanic acid is essential to overcome beta-lactamase producing organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate as it primarily covers \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E but lacks coverage against the oral flora commonly encountered in human bite wounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would provide inadequate coverage against \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and beta-lactamase producing organisms commonly found in these injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECephalexin\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide adequate coverage against anaerobic organisms and \u003Cem\u003EEikenella corrodens\u003C/em\u003E, which are important pathogens in human bite injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E alone would only cover anaerobic organisms and would miss many important aerobic pathogens involved in these infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to appropriate antibiotic therapy, management should include thorough wound cleaning, tetanus prophylaxis if indicated, and careful assessment for underlying tendon or joint involvement. Early specialist referral may be needed if there is evidence of deep structure involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amoxicillin-clavulanate is the first-line empirical antibiotic for human bite infections due to its coverage of oral flora and skin organisms.","Clenched-fist injuries should be considered human bites due to contact with oral flora.","Early wound care and antibiotics are essential to prevent complications of human bite injuries."],"references":["Shewring DJ, Trickett RW, Subramanian KN, Hnyda R. The management of clenched fist \u0027fight bite\u0027 injuries of the hand. J Hand Surg Eur Vol. 2015 Oct;40(8):819-24. doi: 10.1177/1753193415576249. Epub 2015 Mar 14. PMID: 25770897. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25770897/","Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {01 Nov 2024}. https://www.tg.org.au","Maniscalco K, Edens MA. Human Bites. [Updated 2023 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430764/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92321"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14786"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92321"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T18:10:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T18:11:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7477"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109963"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun